<%= faq_schema([
  { question: "How do I calculate unit price?", answer: "Divide the total price by the quantity. For example, if a 24-oz bottle costs $3.99, the unit price is $3.99 / 24 = $0.1663 per ounce. Compare this to another product's unit price to determine which offers better value. Always make sure you are comparing the same units (ounces to ounces, pounds to pounds, etc.)." },
  { question: "Is the bigger package always the better deal?", answer: "Not always. While bulk packages often have a lower unit price, this is not guaranteed. Stores sometimes put smaller sizes on sale, making them temporarily cheaper per unit. Also, if you cannot use the entire quantity before it expires, the savings are wasted. Always calculate and compare unit prices rather than assuming bigger means cheaper." },
  { question: "What is the difference between unit price and total price?", answer: "Total price is what you pay at the register for the entire package. Unit price is the cost per individual unit of measurement (per ounce, per count, per pound, etc.). Unit price allows you to compare products of different sizes on an equal basis, making it the better metric for value comparison." },
  { question: "How can I save money at the grocery store using unit prices?", answer: "Many store price tags include the unit price in small print. Compare unit prices across different brands and package sizes for the same product. Store brands often have lower unit prices than name brands. Check if buying two smaller packages is cheaper than one large one. Keep a mental note of unit prices for items you buy regularly so you can spot genuine deals." },
  { question: "Should I always buy the cheapest unit price option?", answer: "Not necessarily. Consider quality differences between brands, shelf life (bulk perishables may spoil before you use them), storage space limitations, and your actual consumption rate. A lower unit price only saves money if you use the product before it goes bad. For non-perishable items you use regularly, the lowest unit price is usually the best choice." }
]) %>

